title: My Stroke Story
author: Wen
category: The story of my life before and after stroke

sentences.content: My name is Ronlyn Goo.
I live in Saratoga, California.
I was born in 1962 in San Francisco.
I grew up in Pacifica.
My dad and mom raised me and my two younger sisters, Jaylynne and Stacy.
I studied Chemical Engineering at UC Berkeley.
I met Wen Eng, a fellow chemical engineering major in junior year.
I graduated in 1985.
I worked at Dow Chemical after college.
I started as a process engineer.
My last position was in research and product development.
Then I went to Stanford GSB for an MBA.
After Stanford, I was a management consultant at CSC Index.
I ran my own consulting company Proquest Systems after that.
I also led a Center for Innovation for Mission College.
I have been married to my spouse for almost 30 years.
Wen and I met in college.
We have two children, David and Robert.
David is 27 years old.
He went to Stanford.
He earned a couple degrees in computer science.
He founded a technology company called Bunker Hill Health in Palo Alto.
Robert is 25 years old.
He went to Caltech.
He majored in computer science and history.
He works for a startup in San Francisco.
I was a CEO presenting to my board when I had my stroke.
I had a severe hemorrhagic stroke in September 2015.
About 13% of stroke survivors were like me.
About one out of three died within 30 days.
About 25% survive five years
I was initially in a coma for a week.
I woke with right side impairment and severe aphasia.
I could only speak one word: “after”.
After spending a month in the neuro ICU, I had a month in the stroke recovery ward.
Then I had transitional rehab at home followed by nearly 400 out-patient therapy sessions.
I feel lucky because more than one third of hemorrhagic stroke victims do not live passed the first few days and up to two thirds do not live a 1 year after stroke.
I walk around the park near my home.
I walk up to ten laps in an hour.
I practice staying balanced, taking a bigger left step and landing it with a heel strike.
I constantly practice listening and speaking during the walk.
I also attend SPARC at San Jose State.
On Fridays, I have 1:1 Speech Therapy, Book club reading Hidden Figures, and Aphasia choir.
I also attend ATP at Cal State East Bay. On Mondays, I have Book Club at Becoming by Michelle Obama, Wednesdays: Brain Games, Tuesday/Thursdays exercising, Fridays with Choir.
I attend Aphasia Recovery Connection & Lingraphica
I attend speech therapy at Brooklyn College.
Now, I attend Voices of Hope for Aphasia at “Name That Song”, Aphasia Book Club where we are currently reading Where the Crawdads Sing, art, reading and writing group, chat and exercises.
I attend Nova Southeastern with “Stories of Perseverance” and other.
Speech Recovery Pathways
Stanford Healing Strokes Art Therapy, National Aphasia Association and Aphasia Game Night.
I ride my recumbent tricycle.
It's also known as a tadpole.
It is low to the ground so it feels very stable at any speed.
I read (listen to) books using audible.
The Nightingale by Kristin Hannah, Where the Crawdads by Delia Owens and Water for Elephants by Sara Gruen
I paint in watercolors
I sing
I bake desserts.
I am gardening.
I am singing in choirs.
Queens Library
Since my stroke, I travelled to Hawaii and up and down the west coast.
I have been to Seattle, Portland, Eugene, San Francisco, Monterey, Carmel, Santa Barbara, Los Angeles, and San Diego.
I am trying my hardest to get better!!!
